{{italic title}}
{{Other uses|Living Planet (disambiguation)}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}

The '''''Living Planet Report''''' is  published every two years by the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] since 1998. It is based on the [[Living Planet Index]] and [[ecological footprint]] calculations.

The ''Living Planet Report'' is the world's leading, science-based analysis on the health of our planet and the impact of human activity.  Humanity's demands exceed the Earth's capacity to sustain us.<ref name=report2016>{{cite report|url=http://awsassets.panda.org/downloads/lpr_living_planet_report_2016.pdf |title=''Living Planet Report'' 2016: Risk and resilience in a new era |publisher=[[World Wildlife Fund]] |isbn=978-2-940529-40-7 |pages=1–74 |accessdate=29 October 2016}} ([http://awsassets.panda.org/downloads/lpr_living_planet_report_2016_summary.pdf Summary]).</ref>

The 2018 report found a "decline of 60% in population sizes" of vertebrate species overall from 1970 to 2014. The tropics of South and Central America had an 89% loss compared to 1970. The 2018 report calls for new goals post-2020 alongside those of the [[Convention on Biological Diversity]], the [[Paris Agreement|Paris Climate Agreement]] and the [[Sustainable Development Goals]].<ref name=report2018>{{cite report |title=''Living Planet Report'' 2018: Aiming higher |url=http://assets.wwf.ca/downloads/lpr2018_full_report_spreads.pdf |publisher=World Wildlife Fund |isbn=978-2-940529-90-2 |pages=1–75 |accessdate=31 October 2018}} ([http://assets.wwf.ca/downloads/lpr2018_summary_report_pages.pdf Summary]).</ref>

== Editions ==
The first version of the ''Living Planet Report'' was published on 1998.<ref>[http://d2ouvy59p0dg6k.cloudfront.net/downloads/livingplanetreport98.pdf ''Living Planet Report'' 1998]. World Wide Fund for Nature. Retrieved 29 October 2016.</ref> Following versions in 1999,<ref>[http://awsassets.panda.org/downloads/lpr_living_planet_report_1999.pdf ''Living Planet Report'' 1999]. World Wide Fund for Nature. Retrieved 29 October 2016.</ref> 2000, 2002, 2004, 2006, 2008, 2010, 2012, 2014, 2016, and 2018.<ref name=report2016/><ref name=report2018/>

