[[Category:Ancient Roman religion]] [[Category:Mithraic mysteries]] [[Category:Cattle in religion]] [[Category:Mythological bulls]]

{{short description|A northwesterly extension of the Ottawa-Bonnechere Graben}} [[File:Ottawabonnecheregrabenmap.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of the Ottawa-Bonnechere and Timiskaming grabens]] The '''Timiskaming Graben''' is a {{nowrap|{{Convert|400|km|mi|abbr=on}}}} long and {{nowrap|{{Convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}}}} wide [[depression (geology)|depression]] straddling the [[Ontario]]–[[Quebec]] border in [[Eastern Canada]].<ref name="QJ">{{cite journal|last=Doughty|first=Michael|last2=Eyles|first2=Nick|last3=Daurio|first3=Louise|url=https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/GC/article/view/18397/19865|title=Ongoing Neotectonic Activity in the Timiskaming ─ Kipawa Area of Ontario and Québec|journal=Geoscience Canada|publisher=[[Geological Association of Canada]]|year=2010|volume=37|issue=3|accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|last3=|first3=|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/sed.12002|title=High‐resolution seismic reflection profiling of neotectonic faults in Lake Timiskaming, Timiskaming Graben, Ontario‐Quebec, Canada|journal=Sedimentology|publisher=International Association of Sedimentologists|year=2012|accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref> It is a northwesterly extension of the [[Ottawa-Bonnechere Graben]], a [[Aulacogen|failed arm]] of the [[Saint Lawrence rift system]] which is related to the opening of the [[Iapetus Ocean]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Doughty|first=M.|last2=Eyles|first2=Carolyn|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/252108799_Active_Neotectonic_Structures_in_Glacial_and_Postglacial_Sediment_in_Lake_Timiskaming_Timiskaming_Graben_OntarioQuebec_Canada|title=Active Neotectonic Structures in Glacial and Postglacial Sediment in Lake Timiskaming, Timiskaming Graben, Ontario/Quebec Canada|publisher=[[ResearchGate]]|year=2009|accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref name="SI">{{Cite journal | last = Kumarapeli | first = S. | title = Origin and development of the Ottawa Graben | publisher = [[Astrophysics Data System]] | year = 1981 |pages = 114, 115, 116 | postscript = <!--None--> | bibcode = 1981LPICo.457..114K }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Alain |last=Tremblay |first2=Yvon |last2=Lemieux |chapter=Supracrustal faults of the St. Lawrence rift system between Cap-Tourmente and Baie-Saint-Paul, Quebec |title=Current Research 2001-D15 |publisher=[[Natural Resources Canada]] |isbn=0-662-29890-X |id=M44-2001/D15E-IN |chapterurl=http://dsp-psd.pwgsc.gc.ca/Collection/M44-2001-D15E.pdf |year=2001}}</ref>
Formation of the Timiskaming Graben corresponded with collapse of the regional [[crust (geology)|crust]] along the Quinze Dam and Cross Lake faults possibly as early as 2.4&nbsp;billion years ago. It was then reactivated during periods of [[extensional tectonics|crustal extension]] related to the breakups of [[supercontinent]]s [[Rodinia]] and [[Pangaea]] and during [[compression (geology)|compression]] related to the various [[orogeny|orogenies]] that formed the [[Appalachian Mountains]]. The Timiskaming Graben is now partially filled by [[Lake Timiskaming]], a {{nowrap|{{Convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}}}} long successor to the much larger glacial Lake Barlow which drained at the end of the [[last glacial period]] about 8,000&nbsp;years ago.<ref name="QJ"/>
The Timiskaming Graben is a seismically active structure in the [[Western Quebec Seismic Zone]].<ref name="QJ"/> Reactivation of faults has resulted in [[earthquake]]s, such as the [[1935 Timiskaming earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bent|first=Allison L.|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF00876667|title=Am improved source mechanism for the 1935 Timiskaming, Quebec earthquake from regional waveforms|journal=pure and applied geophysics|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]]|year=1994|accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref>
